observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Direct officers and employees with cash advances to immediately submit their liquidation papers, otherwise, require the immediate withholding of salary of those officers and employees who were unable to comply with the requirement;
Require the Municipal Accountant to closely monitor the liquidation of outstanding cash advances and serve again written demand on the submission of liquidation reports (LR) within the reglementary period and maintain subsidiary ledgers;
Stop the practice of granting additional cash advances to those who have unliquidated cash advances; and
Recover the documents relevant to the long outstanding cash advances and conduct verification, analysis and validation of them to determine their settlement/collectability and pursue collection, refund or liquidation, if warranted.

We recommended that Management:
Enforce submission of the lacking documents, enumerated in Annex B, on the aforementioned disbursements and explain the noted deficiencies;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to strengthen its internal control in the pre-audit of financial transactions and ensure that the supporting documents are complete and accurate, otherwise, refrain from processing the claims or payments of the same;
Require the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to exercise strictest scrutiny in the preparation of bidding documents, conduct of procurement activities in accordance with the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 and other relevant procurement guidelines and supporting the transactions with complete documentary requirements pursuant to COA Circular No. 2012-001;
Require the contractors to submit warranty securities for the completed and acceptance infrastructure projects pursuant to Section 62.2.3 of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184; and
Consider issuing Certificate of Acceptance one year after completion of the project in order for the contractor to be liable for any defects or damages that may be incurred within the defect liability period.

We recommended that Management require the LSB to strictly comply with the provisions of DepEd-DBM-DILG JC No. 1, s. 2017 and Section 272 of RA No. 7160, such as to:
Formulate a three-year program indicating strategic prioritization policies in the allocation of the SEF to schools;
Require the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to submit to the LSB, not later than July 15 of the current year, the actual SEF income of the preceding periods and the estimated income of the succeeding periods to appropriately project a realistic SET collectible in the ensuing year;
Prepare a SEF Budget of the ensuing year not later than October 31 of the current year, ensuring that the PPAs for ECCD be incorporated in this Budget and incorporating thereof the unappropriated balances of the prior years; and
Submit the quarterly and annual reports on SEF utilization using the prescribed form, prepared by the Local Accountant, to the DepEd Central Office and COA within the prescribed period.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Evaluate the composition of the Municipality’s SWMB and look for possible members that could qualify to complete the prescribed lineup;
Direct the SWM Focal Person prioritize the approval of the SWMP that will ensure effective and efficient management of solid wastes generated within the Municipality;
Facilitate the issuance of an ordinance, in partnership with the Local Sanggunian, for the safe closure and rehabilitation of the Municipality’s existing dumpsite at Barangay Bolod (Poblacion) and fast-track the approval of the proposed lot for the sanitary landfill. For the meantime, the Municipality must utilize the temporary Residual Containment Area (RCA) for the residual management and operate it based on the guidelines provided by the Environment Management Bureau (EMB); and
Provide additional garbage trucks that is enough to collect all the residual and special wastes from all the barangays of the Municipality and not just from Barangay Bolod and Terraplin.
We further recommend that the Local Sanggunian prioritize the approval of the 2024 Annual Budget in order for the implementation of priority projects relevant to the SWM, such as but not limited to the rehabilitation of the open dumpsites, procurement of lot for the sanitary landfill, provision of equipment for the proper collection and disposal of solid waste of the Municipality, etc.

We recommended that Management:

Create Reconstitute or reactivate the Inventory Committee through the issuance of an executive order. Subsequently, direct them to prepare the PIP for approval of the Chief Executive and submit the same to the Audit Team at least ten calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory-taking activities;

Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct the physical count of all PPE following the guidelines outlined in COA Circular No. 2020-006 and submit the RPCPPE to the Audit Team; 

Direct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to reconcile their respective PPE records.

Require the Municipal Accounting Office to maintain complete and updated PPELCs to support GL account balances and the MTO to keep corresponding PCs for control purposes;

In addition, we recommended that the Municipal Accounting Office concerned personnel trace back prior years’ acquisitions to have complete details of the PPE accounts that will serve as basis in the computation of depreciation, in order to present true value of the depreciable PPE in the FS.

Furthermore, we recommended that the Municipal Accountant recompute the CY 2021 depreciation expenses for those PPE acquired prior to December 31, 2014 and make the necessary adjustments on the affected accounts.

We recommended that Management:

Exhaust all possible means to require the concerned officers and employees to liquidate/settle immediately their outstanding cash advances by demanding the immediate submission of duly accomplished liquidation reports or to refund the cash still in their possession;

Immediately stop the grant of additional cash advances to all officers and employees with unliquidated cash advances until such time that previous cash advances are fully settled;

Strengthen the operation of preventive and monitoring controls to ensure correct recording of cash advances and timely submission of liquidation documents for full accounting of balances of all cash advances to ensure compliance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002;

Require the officers and employees who will retire, resign or transfer to liquidate their outstanding cash advances prior to the approval of their clearances;

Stop the practice of granting cash advances for infrastructure projects and ensure that cash advances are with legally authorized specific purpose;

Refrain from processing claims against any fund unless supported with complete documentation and strictly abide by the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 and Section 89 of PD No. 1445; and

Institute appropriate legal actions/sanctions such as suspension of salaries of those erring accountable officers/employees for the continued non-compliance with the existing laws, rules and regulations on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances, if warranted.

We recommended that Management:

Require the MDRRMC to prepare the LDRRMFIP annually and furnish the Audit Team with a copy thereof;

Direct the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the MDRRMO to regularly prepare every month the Report on the Sources and Utilization of LDRRMF using the prescribed format in COA Circular No. 2012-002; 

Submit such report on or before the 15th day after the end of the month through the LDRRMC and LDC to the Audit Team in compliance with the reportorial requirements of the aforementioned COA Circular;

Enjoin the LDRRMO to exert more effort in implementing actions and measures pertaining to all aspects of disaster risk reduction and management towards building a disaster-resilient LGU and communities; and

Closely monitor the implementation of all PPAs under the LDRRMF to facilitate corrective action, if any, and the timely reprogramming and reallocation of the fund for its optimum utilization.

We recommended that Management:

Submit the 10-year Municipal SWM Plan to NSWMC for approval to serve as guide for the efficient management of solid waste generated within the Municipality’s jurisdiction;

Encourage and provide needed assistance to the remaining 15 barangays to establish their own MRFs for the collection, segregation, recycling of biodegradable, recyclable, compostable and reusable wastes;

Provide adequate assistance in restoring the six not functional barangay MRFs; and

Provide the necessary training for SWM personnel to ensure that solid wastes are properly handled and that the risk of hazards to them and to the public are avoided or minimized.

We recommended that Management:
Enjoin the LDRRMO to exert more effort in implementing actions and measures pertaining to all aspects of disaster risk reduction and management towards building a disaster-resilient LGU and communities;
Closely monitor the implementation of all PPAs under the LDRRMF to facilitate corrective action, if any, and the timely reprogramming and reallocation of the fund for its optimum utilization;
Direct the LDRRMO to prepare the annual LDRRMFIP detailing all the PPAs to be funded in accordance with COA Circular 2012-002 to ensure proper evaluation of the same;
Advise the Municipal Budget Officer see to it that all charges in the LDRRMF are related to four (4) thematic areas of disaster risk reduction and management as prescribed in NDRRMC, DBM and DILG JMC 2013-1; and
Instruct the LDRRMO to prepare and submit the monthly Report on the Sources and Utilization of LDRRMF on time and facilitate monitoring of the accomplishment vis-à-vis the targeted projects for effective and efficient utilization of the fund.

We recommended that Management:
Submit the 10-year Municipal SWM Plan to NSWMC for approval to serve as guide for the efficient management of solid waste generated within the Municipality’s jurisdiction;
Prioritize SWM programs and projects by providing/allocating enough budget for their full implementation;
Encourage and provide needed assistance to the remaining 15 barangays to establish their own MRFs for the collection, segregation, recycling of biodegradable, recyclable, compostable and reusable wastes;
Provide adequate assistance in restoring the six not functional barangay MRFs;
Provide the necessary training for SWM personnel to ensure that solid wastes are properly handled and that the risk of hazards to them and to the public are avoided or minimized; and
Exert continuous effort in preserving and protecting the environment by implementing the environmental laws as mandated under RA No. 9003.

Closely monitor the created Inventory Committee, to conduct the annual physical count of all its PPE and submit the corresponding RPCPPE to the Office of the Auditor;

Evaluate the Agency’s property and supply management system, identify lapses therein and install corrective measures thereof;

Instruct the Municipal Engineer to furnish the Inventory Committee documents pertaining to the details of PPE accounts such as infrastructure assets, buildings and other structures including the on-going constructions to facilitate reconciliation with the accounting records; and 

Direct the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to maintain complete property records required from their respective Offices and reconcile the same. 

Strict adherence to existing laws, auditing rules and regulations in the proper management of government properties is also enjoined.

The Office of the Municipal Accountant to submit to the Auditor the supporting documents of all accumulated accounts payable as reflected in the Schedule of Accounts Payable as of December 31, 2020 to back up the authenticity of the recorded obligations in the books of accounts of the Municipal Government;

In-depth evaluation to identify the veracity, nature and claim of the recorded payables both for the current and prior year’s ledgers/files to determine which are valid claims or fictitious accounts; and

The Office of the Municipal Accountant to take up the appropriate reversion/adjustments in the books of the LGU for those established transactions with no valid claimants and with dormant accounts in order to have a fair presentation of accounts in the FS.

We recommended and reiterated that Management:
8. Closely monitor the created Inventory Committee, to conduct the annual physical count of all its PPE and submit the corresponding RPCPPE to the Office of the Auditor;
9. Evaluate the Agency’s property and supply management system, identify lapses therein and install corrective measures thereof;
10. Instruct the Municipal Engineer to furnish the Inventory Committee documents pertaining to the details of PPE accounts such as infrastructure assets, buildings and other structures including the on-going constructions to facilitate reconciliation with the accounting records; and
11. Direct the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to maintain the respective complete property records required from their Offices and reconcile their respective records.
12. Strict adherence to existing laws, auditing rules and regulations in the proper management of government properties is also enjoined.

We recommended and reiterated that Management:
13. Require the concerned LGU personnel to immediately prepare and submit the liquidation reports with complete supporting documents relative to the utilization of trust funds received from these NGAs in accordance with the MOA;
14. For the completed projects, cause the return of excess funds to the Source Agency in compliance with the guidelines of COA Circular No. 94-013;
15. Require the officials concerned the immediate implementation of priority projects/programs given by NGAs. Proper coordination among the concerned officials-in-charge of the implementation of the PPAs must be undertaken in order to fast track the immediate implementation and completion thereof at the earliest possible time so that the intended beneficiaries could avail the benefits that could be derived therefrom;
16. Submit the complete documents in connection with the downloaded funds which are still unliquidated from the NGAs covering the CY 2018 and prior years, considering the longer period of time that has elapsed for its liquidation, to the Source Agencies. Likewise, require the immediate submission to the Audit Team of the technical documents for all completed projects as requirements for the technical evaluation and inspection of the COA Technical Audit Service (TAS) personnel; and
17. Strictly adhere to existing guidelines governing the rendition of accounts including submission of copies of contracts/MOAs. Direct the Municipal Accountant to require the attachment of complete supporting documents on the duly processed disbursement vouchers pertaining to the downloaded funds before effecting payment and promptly submit to the Audit Team within the prescribed period.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive ensure that:
18. The Municipality strengthen the GFPS by appointing/designating GAD Focal Person to handle and spearhead the GAD related concerns and issues;
19. The DILG issue the Certificate of Endorsement on the prescribed LGU GPB and Review of GAD AR;
20. A GAD Database be developed and maintained as well as regularly updated as sources of relevant information for a systematic planning, programming and policy formulation in order to address the priority gender issues;
21. Gender analysis be conducted on the PPAs to determine which among them are responsive to the identified gender issues; and
22. Monitoring and evaluation system be established to periodically assess the GAD related accomplishments and significant concerns.

We recommended the following recommendations to the Local Chief Executive to address the foregoing audit observation, to wit:

The MDRRMO in close coordination with the MDRRMC be required to prepare a well-planned/studied  LDRRMFIP which must also include under a separate caption, the list of projects and activities charged to the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years amounting to Ᵽ13,269,788.17 which must be implemented as planned in order to optimize utilization and bring the desired benefits to its constituents and to avoid future reversion of LDRRMF to the General Fund. The LGU must ensure the efficient utilization of the LDRRM Fund in order that the objectives of the various programs, projects and activities funded therefrom are achieved;
Full implement the Capital Outlay Fund allocation amounting to Ᵽ1,785,053.00. Install monitoring mechanism to see to it that the ensuing capital outlays and other programs must be implemented on schedule;
Submit Monthly Report on the Sources and Utilization of DRRM Fund; and

Strict compliance with COA Circular No. 2012-002 and RA No. 10121 is enjoined.

We recommended and reiterated that Management,
Convene the Inventory Committee, conduct the annual physical count of all its property, plant and equipment and submit the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RCPPE) to the Office of the Auditor;
Evaluate the Agency’s property and supply management system, identify lapses therein and correct the same the soonest;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer and Acting Municipal Accountant to maintain the respective complete property records required from their offices and reconcile their records; and
Strict adherence to existing laws, auditing rules and regulations in the proper management of government properties is required.

We recommended the Municipal Mayor to instruct the following:
Municipal Accountant to prepare the adjusting entries to reclassify other PPE items that had been recorded in School Buildings account. Ensure that future construction/improvement of school buildings and its accessory equipment are recorded in their proper account;
Local School Board, Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to stop budgeting and paying, respectively, expenses which are not priority expenditures under the Special Education Fund, otherwise they will be disallowed in audit;
Municipal Treasurer to refrain from granting cash advances to accountable officers which payments can be made directly to the supplier/contractor and in order for the Municipality to deduct and withhold applicable taxes and remit the same in accordance with the BIR Revenue Regulations;
District Supervisor to provide a justification letter for the request of additional allowances despite receipt of allowance from the Province for the same competition; and
Project implementer exert more efforts in collecting the amounts due from the student beneficiaries, establish alternative payment schemes and plans for defaulting borrowers to enforce efficient collection
